About
As the Hermitage Amsterdam, and now as H’ART Museum, we have always housed some of the most unique and famous art, from present day to antiquity. Connecting the art world in new ways and bringing it to Amsterdam for everyone to enjoy. Now we form a unique global art collective together with world-renowned international partners The British Museum, Centre Pompidou, and SAAM (Smithsonian American Art Museum), which brings the UK, France, USA, and the Netherlands together as never before. We want to inspire people through powerful, relevant, and heartfelt art.
Duration: 1-2 hours

Julius Caesar in Amsterdam, lost in this exhibition
Nov 2023 • Couples
The current exhibition JULIUS CAESAR IN AMSTERDAM AS NEVER BEFORE is not worth the ticket. It costs 22.50, is incomplete and pretentious. The busts present-missing the Tusculum and the Chiaramonti-look like stand-ins for Caesar; the 3D facial reconstruction (Leiden) has grotesque effects: Caesar looks like a Gargamel; while the recent and more plausible photographic reconstruction, implemented on the basis of the statue that emerged from the Terracina Theater, is ignored; last but not least, no evidence of the Tencteri/Usipeti massacre is provided, but only hints about the bone remains from the Dutch village of Kessel-Lith. Although the thesis of genocide in Gaul was already known in Antiquity because it was argued by Cato the Minor before the Senate and confirmed by Pliny the Elder (1,200,000 dead), the historical reinterpretation of war events of 2,000 years ago on the basis of modern legal notions, principles or ethical rules, it seems to me to be misleading and of poor usefulness for inexperienced people.

Expected more
Apr 2023
I visited the Hermitage Amsterdam Museum and not the other museums in the building. I was expecting a lot more (like more about the history of the city itself, its different neighbourhoods, etc.) The exhibitions were random and I didn't really see how they were connected (like dresses made of feathers, and information about the housing crisis, videos where locals talked about how they found a place to live in the city, etc.) also it seemed as though the place was going under refurbishment, and there weren't a lot of places to sit down. It was also difficult to find because the location moved pretty far away from its original location, so it took me over an hour to get to it in the end (other people in the street were confused about where to enter as well). At least the luggage storage was free and I got to hide away from the rain for an hour or so. I expected more given the cost.

Interesting Dutch museum
Mar 2023 • Couples
This museum currently has the Leiden collection on display, which was well done.

The audio tour did a good job discussing what was being painted for someone not familiar with the subject matter.

The Amsterdam Museum also had an exhibit that was quite interesting on the West Indies colinization and slave trade as as well as an exhibit on the plane crash in Amsterdam in 1992 and its affects on children.

In addition, there was a good exhibit on handcrafts and the history of housing in Amsterdam.

We enjoyed our visit and I am glad the were able to pivot after severing ties with their Russian counterpart.

jolav12
The Netherlands
242 contributions
There is not really a choice between the options you mention. The all-in ticket is €29.95 for adults, but if you have the Museumkaart (Museum Card) it's only €10. The Museum Card costs about €60 for a year and gives free access to lots of Dutch museums, but I'm not sure if it's available to people that don't live in the Netherlands.

The NY Times said this was good for kids. Is it? Is it good for a toddler? (2 years old)
Written July 25, 2015
luvroma2
1,943 contributions
You are from Brooklyn, so I am sure you have been to the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Do you think your 2 year old would enjoy the Metropolitan Museum? It is the same sort of museum, albeit on a much smaller scale. I have been to the Hermitage many times. The shows and exhibits change periodically. I can say I have never been to one that would hold a 2 year old's attention. Plus if you plan to use a stroller, some of the rooms are so small that it is difficult for people to maneuver, let alone adding a stroller to the mix. The more popular exhibits get very crowded and that can be frightening for a toddler having all those people crowding around. There are many more places in Amsterdam that you and your toddler would enjoy more than the Hermitage. It is an adult museum. I an not sure what the New York Times article meant because it is not a "static" museum, so maybe they were referencing perhaps the Napoleon exhibit which could interest a 10 year old - but not a 2 year old.
